[{"id":"VR444854","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of two blocks on a horizontal surface. Block 1 is positioned to the left of block 2, and a horizontal spring is attached to the left edge of block 2. Block 1 is moving to the right across the horizontal surface towards the horizontal spring.\" height=\"48\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR444854.g14.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Block&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> slides rightward on the floor toward an ideal spring attached to block&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, as shown. At time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"t sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, block&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> reaches the spring and starts compressing it as block&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> also starts to slide to the right. At a later time, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub 2\"><math alttext=\"t sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, block&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> loses contact with the spring. Both blocks slide with negligible friction. Taking rightward as positive, which pair of graphs could represent the acceleration of block&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and the center-of-mass acceleration of the two-block system?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR444854_rubric","choicesHtml":["<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n\n<img alt=\"The figure shows two graphs in a coordinate plane, with the origin labeled O. Each graph has the horizontal axis labeled “Time,” and the values t sub 1 and t sub 2, are indicated. The first graph is labeled “Acceleration of Block 2” and the second graph is labeled “Center-of-Mass Acceleration.” In the first graph, the graph is a curve that begins at the origin and moves horizontally to the right to the value t sub 1. It then moves upward and to the right and reaches a peak at a point about halfway between t sub 1 and t sub 2, and then moves downward and to the right until it reaches the horizontal axis at the value t sub 2. It then moves horizontally to the right until it ends. In the second graph, the graph is a line that begins at the origin and moves horizontally to the right, passing through t sub 1 and t sub 2 before it ends.\" height=\"171\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR444854.g16.png\" width=\"370\"></div>","<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n\n<img alt=\"The figure shows two graphs in a coordinate plane, with the origin labeled O. Each graph has the horizontal axis labeled “Time,” and the values t sub 1 and t sub 2, are indicated. The first graph is labeled “Acceleration of Block 2” and the second graph is labeled “Center-of-Mass Acceleration.” In the first graph, the graph is a curve that begins at the origin and moves horizontally to the right to the value t sub 1. It then moves upward and to the right until it reaches a point about halfway between t sub 1 and t sub 2. From here, the curve moves horizontally to the right until it ends. In the second graph, the graph is a line that begins at the origin and moves horizontally to the right, passing through t sub 1 and t sub 2 before it ends.\" height=\"171\" src=\"h